**Russian General Lapin 'Helped' Ukrainian Army in Kursk Region**
Russian General Alexander Lapin has been involved in another scandal during the full-scale invasion of Ukraine. In the fall of 2022, Chechen leader Ramzan Kadyrov strongly criticized Lapin for the withdrawal of Russian troops from Liman and the breakthrough of the Ukrainian army on the Donetsk front. In the spring of 2024, Lapin disbanded the interagency council responsible for defending border regions, according to The Wall Street Journal, citing a source in Russian security services. In August, the Ukrainian army broke through the Russian defense and occupied part of the Kursk region. Before the Ukrainian operation, Lapin's command warned Moscow that the Ukrainian army was increasing its numbers on the front line, but this warning was ignored. As a result, Ukrainian troops did not meet resistance on neutral territory near the border, and inside Russia, there were no territorial defense forces that could slow down their advance. Additionally, the Ukrainian army cut off communication, and Russian troops were unable to contact their command and became scattered in the forest. Lapin's forces, despite having intelligence on the Ukrainian army's movements, failed to strengthen defensive lines or set up mines, as the Russian army did in 2023 to repel a large Ukrainian counterattack. Furthermore, Russian troops faced a critical shortage of personnel. The Wall Street Journal notes that not only Lapin, but also the Russian military leadership, often disconnected from the realities of the battlefield, 'opened the gates' for the Ukrainian advance. 'This is not the first time that Lapin's army has faced poor planning and a lack of personnel. In the fall of 2022, Chechen leader Ramzan Kadyrov strongly criticized Lapin, first for the withdrawal of Russian troops from Liman, and then for the breakthrough of the Ukrainian army on the Donetsk front. Kadyrov called Lapin 'ineffective' and stated that the general did not provide mobilized soldiers with ammunition and communication, while he himself 'sat' in Lugansk. At the time, Lapin was commander of the Central Military District. In November, he was removed from his position, but in January 2023, he was appointed head of the Main Staff of the Ground Forces of the Armed Forces of Russia. In May 2024, Lapin took over as commander of the Leningrad Military District, created two months earlier.
