**Monday, August 19, 2024 E-Paper**
Ukrainian forces have made significant gains in their incursion into Russia, capturing the town of Sudzha and pushing deep into Russian territory. According to Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy, the town is 'fully under his troops' control.' The operation has led to the evacuation of over 120,000 civilians and the capture of at least 100 Russian troops. While the incursion has been seen as a major morale boost for Ukraine, it has not yet dented Russia's overall strategic advantage. The full scope of the Kursk operation remains unclear, including how long Ukraine plans to hold Russian territory and to what end. Ukrainian officials have said that diverting Russian reserves from the main battlegrounds in eastern Ukraine is a minimum aim of the operation, but Moscow has shown no signs of withdrawing significant numbers of troops. Zelenskyy has said that Ukraine will establish a command office in Sudzha to coordinate aid and military affairs, suggesting that Ukraine may plan to remain in the Kursk region long-term. 'It is widely seen as a major morale boost for a country and an army struggling to fend off steady Russian advances more than two years after Moscow sent troops into Ukraine,' said an AP journalist. 'But, so far, it has not dented Russia's overall strategic advantage.'
