**Ukraine Launches Major Cross-Border Counterattack Against Russia**
Ukraine launched a major cross-border counterattack against Russia, with clashes reported between the two sides in the Kursk region. According to reports, Ukrainian forces advanced at least 20 kilometers into the region, with the Russian Defense Ministry stating that they had sent additional troops, tanks, and artillery to the area to push back the Ukrainian forces. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky acknowledged the advance on Russian territory, saying that the conflict had become a 'battle for the borders' and that Ukraine was exerting pressure on the 'aggressive' side. The Kremlin declared a federal emergency in the region, with 76,000 people evacuated. Russian President Vladimir Putin held a meeting with government officials to discuss the situation in Kursk, saying that 'there are very important questions about the fight against terrorism' on the agenda. Putin also announced that 'operations to combat terrorism' would be launched in the cities of Kursk, Belgorod, and Bryansk. This comes after Putin stated in February 2022 that the Minsk agreements were no longer in effect. Ukraine and Russia had held peace talks in Istanbul in March 2022, but Ukraine later withdrew from the talks. In October 2022, Zelensky signed a decree banning any peace talks with Russia as long as Putin was in power. Russia first invaded Ukraine in 2014, when it annexed Crimea, and later supported separatist rebels in the Donbas region. In February 2022, Russia launched a large-scale invasion of Ukraine, citing the need to 'liberate' the country from 'Nazis'.
